{"cursor":"3874","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Hajji' (, , al-á¸¥ajjÄ« or Ø§ÙØ­Ø§Ø¬ al-á¸¥Äjj, , , , , [[pilgrim]]; sometimes spelled\n'Hadji' or 'Haji') or 'El-Hajj', is an honorific title given to a Muslim person\nwho has successfully completed the Hajj to Mecca, and is often used\nto refer to an elder, since it can take time to accumulate the wealth to fund\nthe travel. The title is placed before a person's name (for instance, Saif Gani\nbecomes Hajji Saif Gani). It is derived from the Arabic al-á¸¤Äjj, which is the\nactive participle of the verb á¸¥ajja 'to make the pilgrimage to Mecca'. The\nalternative form á¸¥ajjÄ« is derived from the name of the Hajj with the adjectival\nsuffix -Ä«, and this was the form adopted by non-Arabic languages. In some areas,\nthe title has been handed down the generations, and has become a family name.\nSuch usage can be seen, for example, in the Bosniak surname HadÅ¾iosmanoviÄ,\nwhich means 'son of Hajji Osman'.\n\nWomen who complete the Hajj are referred to as 'Hajjah' or Ø§ÙØ­Ø§Ø¬Ø© al-\ná¸¤Äjjah., or (in Hausa/Fulani) 'Hajiya'.\n\nIn Arab countries, á¸¤Äjj and á¸¤Äjjah (pronunciation varying based on the form of\nArabic spoken) is a common respectful manner of addressing any older person,\nregardless of whether or not the person in question has actually performed the\npilgrimage.\n\nThe term is also used in the Balkan Christian countries that were once under\nOttoman domination (Bulgaria, Serbia, Greece, Montenegro, Macedonia, Cyprus and\nRomania) for a Christian who had traveled to Jerusalem and the Holy\nLands.\n\nIn Cyprus, where for centuries Christians and Muslims intermixed freely and\nJerusalem is conveniently local, the title became so prevalent as to be\npermanently integrated into some Greek Christian family names, such as\nHajiioannou, regardless of any lack of qualification.\n","linknr":274,"url":"Hajji","recorded":1375066493,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Hajji&action=edit","/w/index